	        Send us your pictures   ·  Send us your stories Seventeen students have been arrested for public violence after clashing with police at the University of KwaZulu-Natal's (UKZN) Westville campus on Monday. Police spokesperson Captain Nqobile Gwala told News24 that about 300 students who had gathered at the campus at about 08:00 threw stones at the police. "There are police vehicles that were damaged during the violent protest," she said. Read: Classes suspended as students, university security clash at UKZN She said the 17 students would appear in court soon for public violence. Police are still at the scene to stabilise the situation, according to Gwala. News24 reported on August 8 that the university had suspended lectures at the Westville campus following a violent confrontation between police and students. Read more: UKZN Westville suspends lectures amid protests The protest came after students raised issues over the administration of the National Student Financial Aid Scheme, shuttle service timetables and amenities at some residences. UKZN spokesperson Normah Zondo said on Monday afternoon that the academic programme, including all tests, had been suspended only at the Westville campus. "The suspension will allow university management to engage with student leadership and find amicable solutions.The programme will resume on Tuesday, she said.Zondo only confirmed the arrest of three students "following violent protest action and the disruption of lectures on the campus this morning". 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.  